<section xml:id="lesson5_2" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
   <title>Mathematical Models</title>

   <section xml:id="what_is_a_mathematical_model" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <title>What is a mathematical model?</title>

      <!-- Diana's original definition of mathematical models; Jen's expanded suggestion (below).
<p>A mathematical model predicts the behavior of some predictable process</p>
-->

      <p> A <term>mathematical model</term> is a mathematical representation of a predictable,
         real-world situation, like dividing a pie between a group of people, that can be used to
         make predictions and solve problems. </p>

      <!-- Rephrased for clarity (below), revert if the original text is preferred. - Jen
<p>In order to solve these problems mathematically, we need a few things:
-->

      <p> In order to develop a mathematical model that we can use to solve these problems, we need
         a few things: <ul>
            <li> Mathematical symbols to express the parts of the problem.</li>
            <li>Mathematical operations to follow to calculate the result.</li>
         </ul>
      </p>

      <!--
<ul>
   <li>Mathematical symbols to express the parts of the problem.</li>
   <li>Mathematical operations to follow to calculate the result.</li>
</ul>
-->

      <p> If the neccessary symbols and operations don't exist, then people invent new symbols and
         define new operations that properly predict the observed behavior. The main point is that
         the mathematics is derived from observations of the real world, not the other way around.
         I'll explain this using a familiar mathematical model: <em>fractions!</em>
      </p>

      <!--
</section>

<section xml:id="fractions_mathematical_model" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Mathematical model for fractions</title>

<p>I'll explain this using a familiar mathematical model - <em>fractions!</em></p>
-->

      <sidebyside widths="70% 30%" valigns="top middle">
         <p>Consider the following problem: <ul>
               <li>You are sharing a pie with three friends.</li>
               <li>You cut the pie into 4 equal pieces.</li>
               <li>Your friend exclaims, <em>“Just because there are four of us, it doesn't mean we
            need to eat the whole pie! I only want half that much!!”</em>
               </li>
               <li>How much of the pie will you give to your friend? </li>
            </ul>
         </p>
         <image source="L5.2_Pie.png" width="50%" />
      </sidebyside>
      <p>
         You are probably so used to solving problems like this in daily life, that you don't think
         about all the steps
         that go into solving it with fractions! Let's explore those aspects.
</p>
   </section>


   <section xml:id="representing_fractional_state" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <title> Representing a fractional state </title>

      <!--
<p> <term>Representing a fractional state</term> </p>
-->

      <p>
         We might ask for “one fourth” when asking for a piece of pie, and this could be translated
         to
         “if the pie were divided into 4 equal-sized parts, then I want one of them.”
</p>

      <p> We can also represent this mathematically with the number of parts you want (numerator)
         placed over the total number of parts (denominator) with a line in between. We can either
         display it with the numerator above the denominator with a horizontal line in between or a
         1 to the left of the 4 with a diagonal line in between. However, you cannot display it as <m>1 \backslash 4</m>
         . </p>
      <image source="L5.2_Fractions.png" width="66%" />

      <!--
<sidebyside widths="15% 25%" valign="top">
    <image source="L5.0-fractionstate.png" width="66%" />
    <image source="L5.0-fractionstate2.png" width="66%" />
</sidebyside>
-->

      <p>The ability to represent fractional states in this way allows us to more clearly state the
         problem:</p>

      <p>
         <ul>
            <li>You are sharing a pie with three friends.</li>
            <li>You cut the pie into 4 equal pieces, each <m>\frac{1}{4}</m> of the pie.</li>
            <li>Your friend exclaims, <em>“Just because there are four of us, it doesn't mean we
               need to eat the whole pie! I only want <m>\frac{1}{2}</m> a piece!!” </em>
            </li>
            <li>How much of the pie will you give to your friend? </li>
         </ul>
      </p>
      <p>Let's review what is involved in performing operations with fractions.</p>
   </section>

   <section xml:id="multiplying_fractions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <title> Multiplying fractions </title>


      <!-- <p>To multiply fractions, we perform this set of operations:</p> -->

      <sidebyside widths="45% 55%" valigns="top bottom">
         <p> To multiply fractions: <ol>
               <li>Multiply the numerators </li>
               <li>Multiply the denominators </li>
               <li>Simplify if necessary </li>
            </ol>
         </p>
         <image source="L5.0-fractionmult.png" width="50%" />
      </sidebyside>


      <!-- <image source="L5.0-fractionmult.png" width="50%"/> -->
      <p>Now let's consider a slightly different question:</p>

      <p>
         <ul>
            <li>You bring two pies to share at a potluck: a pecan pie and an apple pie. </li>
            <li>Both pies have the same radius, but the pecan pie is much more intense than the
               apple pie, so you cut smaller pieces;
               you cut the pecan pie into 10 pieces and the apple pie into 8 pieces.</li>
            <li>When it's time to gather your leftovers: the pecan pie has 5 pieces left, and the
               apple pie has 3 pieces left. </li>
            <li>How much of the total pie is left?</li>
         </ul>
      </p>

      <p> To solve this, you would perform the following steps: <ol>
            <li>Express the leftover pecan pie as a fraction: <m>\frac{5}{10}</m> <em>(5 of 10 pieces remain)</em>
            </li>
            <li>Simplify the pecan pie fraction to be <m>\frac{5}{10} = \frac{1}{2}</m>
            </li>
            <li>Express the leftover apple pie as a fraction: <m>\frac{3}{8}</m> <em>(3 of 8 pieces remain)</em>
            </li>
            <li>Add the fractions</li>
         </ol>
      </p>
      <p>
         Easy-peasy lemon-squeezy, right? Addition is easier than multiplication,
         so adding these fractions should be a piece of cake (or pie), right?
</p>
   </section>

   <section xml:id="adding_fractions" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <title> Adding fractions </title>

      <p>To add fractions, we perform this set of operations: <ol>
            <li>Find the least common denominator (LCD) </li>
            <li>
               <p>Convert the fractions to the LCD: </p>
               <p> To convert 1st fraction: <m> \: \: 1^{st} \: numerator \times \frac{LCD}{1^{st} \: denominator} </m>
               </p>
               <p> To convert 2nd fraction: <m> \: 2^{nd} \: numerator \times \frac{LCD}{2^{nd} \: denominator} </m>
               </p>
            </li>
            <li>Add the numerators (retain the common denominator) </li>
            <li>Simplify if necessary </li>
         </ol>
      </p>
      <image source="L5.2_Fraction_LCM-Equation2.png" width="90%" />

      <p> I know what you're thinking, "Now you just hold on a <!--cotton-pickin'--> minute. That didn't seem easier at
         all!" I must agree with you there. How about we look at an alternate representation:
         Decimals. </p>
   </section>

   <section xml:id="working_with_decimals" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
      <title> Working with Decimals </title>

      <p>
         Notice that if we had expressed these operations as decimals, then the operations would
         have been performed differently. Let's look at the problem of addition, but with decimals:
</p>

      <!--
<p>
<ul>
   <li><m>0.25 \times 0.5 = 0.125</m> <alert>(replace this with the picture of writing all of the
      steps to this starting with one on top of the other)</alert></li>
   <li><m>0.5 + 0.375 = 0.875</m> <alert>(replace this a picture with the 0.5 and 0.375 above and
      below)</alert></li>
</ul>
</p>
-->

      <image source="L5.2_AddingDecimals.gif" width="75%" />

      <p> In this case, addition is easier than multiplication. In fact, multiplication has an
         addition step!</p>

      <p>The important takeaway here is the following:</p>
      <p>
         The mathematical representation you use has advantages and disadvantages in terms of
         readiability vs computation difficulty.
         Fractions are very easy to interpret visually, but they are harder to perform addition.
         Decimals are sometimes harder to interpret,
         but addition and multiplication are easier than with fractions.
</p>

      <!-- original text; playing with formatting - no way to make larger text in PreTeXt.-->
      <!--
<p><alert>(MAKE BIG SOMEHOW)</alert></p>
<p>The important takeaway here is the following:</p>
<p>The mathematical representation you use has <em>advantages</em> & <em>disadvantages</em> in
      terms of readiability vs computation difficulty.</p>
<ul>
   <li>Fractions are very easy to interpret visually, but they are harder to perform addition.</li>
   <li>Decimals are sometimes harder to interpret, but addition and multiplication are easier than
      with fractions.</li>
</ul>
-->

      <p> We are going to see the same tradeoffs in representing quantum state and performing
         quantum operations. We are going to learn two ways to express state <mdash /> one that
         clearly shows the probabilities, and another that corresponds with how to perform
         operations.</p>


   </section>

</section>
